First, the first part: reading t and n. Since in the original Java code, the first program reads t, then for each of t times, reads n. But in our case, t must be 1, so the input is first an integer t (1), then an integer n. So in Fortran, we can read them as:

read*, t, n

But wait, in the first Java program, the first input is t, then for each of t times, it reads n. So the input for the first Java program is t followed by t numbers. But in our case, since the second program needs a single n, the first program's output must be a single number, so t must be 1, so the input is 1 followed by a single n. So the Fortran program must read t (which is 1) and then read n. 

Wait, but in the first Java program, the code is:

Scanner scan = new Scanner(System.in);

int t = scan.nextInt();

for (int i=0; i < t; i++) {

    int n = scan.nextInt();

    System.out.println(maxLeft(n));

} So the input is t followed by t numbers. The output is t numbers. So the second program must read all those t numbers as its input. But the second program's code is written to read a single n. So that suggests that the first program's output is a single number, so t must be 1.
